<font color="#FF0000">WAR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 17 15:01:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To All Here:<br>
     I have been reading many of these posts of Doc Del, Art, Mike, Nurse, Doc Spatz and the others (sorry if I didn't list your name-value your posts equally also).  I have seen this dialog go from a war to a understanding of a sorts, in some cases a new respect. I appreciate greatly your views on this dialog.  I too am a Nam vet.  I grew up in New York City and watched the war as it began and took hold.  I started college and because of funding had to stop for a semester.  Uncle Sam got me then.  I went and enlisted to beat the system and as the recruiter told me &quot;get the most out of my service time&quot;.  I served a year in Nam, came home and watched this country tear itself apart.  I continued me life-NOT where I left off, but not bad either.  Just like many here I too was very bitter and bothered what had happened and what I saw.  In the course of my life and service I made these observations.  These are from my point of view-which doesn't make them wrong, but they may not apply or coincide with those of some of you here.<br>
1.  I grew up with a bunch of guys in a blue collar-middle class area.  Some of us went to Vietnam so didn't.  Having gone to Nam a little later (ie 1970), I had the chance to watch the war affect my neighborhood.  Some of my friends were killed in 1967 and 1968, while others were wounded and came home.  Also, many guys had brothers or cousins that served early in 1965 and they told us how messed up things were over there.  Some of my friends didn't serve-even evaded.  Am I mad they didn't go and I did? No.  It may have disturbed me some at the time and after the war, but if in their heart they can justify their decision, then I guess I am not the one to judge.<br>
2.  Vietnam should have never happened at all.  No, we don't belong fighting anywhere that there are not vital American interests.  Vital interests to me are direct security threats to these country.  If someone is trying to destroy us then we should fight.  I don't always agree with the motives of the evaders and dodgers, but if a war began today that was not in direct defense of our citizens here in the US, I would be the first one to drive my sons to Canada.  I learned about dying for the wrong reasons in Nam.  The crime of the 60's and the Baby Boomer decade, is that after our fathers fought that big war to rescue humanity, the greatest worry of their children should have been what job they wanted or what kind of car the wanted to drive, not whether a gift from the draft board was coming in the mail.  Our entire generation was hurt by the leaders of this nation, who after fighting WW2 should have been more open to peace.  Think of it this way, would this generation have been at each others throats if Vietnam never happened?<br>
3.  This comment is those guys who are bitter about amnesty. I too was very bitter after the war for many years.  At this point now, all that matter is this generation find some peace and open discussion.  What is done is done. We can't go back and change things.  Yes, I still hate those protestors that made the Vet out to be some kind of criminal.  Also I am not found of the certain members of the media (not all) who focused on the the brutal efforts of the US war effort and not the million acts of kindness that soldiers did.  I guess that this generation needs to talk like we are doing here and sort through the times, places and faces that shaped us. I'm not saying we will ever agree on all points, but maybe we can listen.  I wasn't one for peace back then, but how about a wish of peace now.<br>
3.  To those here that opposed the war, I too have learned a lot by hearing your side.  I may not have like what the very small select few of the protestors did, but that doesn't make me a Hawk either.  I guess this war really ended when the majority of American people stopped and realized they were tired of seeing young men go off and die.  Like I said earlier, if you really felt the war was wrong in your heart then I am not the one to judge you, just like I hope you wouldn't judge me.  I'm just glad that we can talk now and discuss what happened then.  Thanks much for that chance.<br>
4.  I think the greatest obstacle for all of us who served was not so much a horrible group of people that attacked us for serving when we came home in was the apathy of our fellow Americans.  At least from where I lived and what I saw, it seemed that most people didn't give a damn about Vietnam or what we went through.  I would have rather had everyone talk a stand on the war either for us or against us, instead of just close your eyes and make it all go away attitude.  When I came back, even the WW2 vets treated us poorly.  I joined the VFW for awhile, and in 1971 the chapter wanted to have a open house for the Nam vets that just got back.  Do you know what they did, they insulted the Nam vets service and brought security in to make sure us violent crazed vets didn't wreck the hall.  Not one vet even raised his voice or even tried to be be disrespectful.  I quit not too long after that.  We Nam vets were on our own.  All we had then was each other.<br>
This is my views on things-thanks for listening to me.  It made me feel better to get this off my chest.  I havn't been able to do all this before.  Thanks guys for listening to this vet.  If anyone would like to discuss anything with me about my views, I would love to talk, it certainly helps. Let's keep this dialog civil and open. <br>
Thanks all!!! 
<p><code>--   (Pointman) </code><p>


